WEBVTT

00:00:01.600 --> 00:00:03.560
Thank you.

00:00:03.570 --> 00:00:09.140
So I'm talking about two years of Skywatch Blue,

00:00:09.140 --> 00:00:11.400
and I'm going to try and talk a little bit.

00:00:11.410 --> 00:00:13.380
The mic isn't picking up your voice, you said it

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:16.400
had something.

00:00:16.410 --> 00:00:17.400
Oh, it fell off.

00:00:17.410 --> 00:00:18.400
Thank you.

00:00:18.410 --> 00:00:21.400
Let's just try clipping it to my shirt.

00:00:21.410 --> 00:00:22.400
All right.

00:00:22.410 --> 00:00:23.400
How's that?

00:00:23.410 --> 00:00:24.400
Thank you.

00:00:24.410 --> 00:00:25.400
All right.

00:00:25.410 --> 00:00:29.080
So I'm talking about two years of running Skywatch Blue

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:29.330
.

00:00:29.390 --> 00:00:33.290
And I'm going to try and impart a few lessons learned

00:00:33.290 --> 00:00:35.430
for community labelers.

00:00:35.470 --> 00:00:38.360
And some of these are hard-won lessons for, you

00:00:38.360 --> 00:00:41.800
know, really anyone who's looking to maybe start a lab

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:45.100
eler, but doesn't have a ton of experience both with

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:49.590
the tech, but also I think with sort of traditional trust

00:00:49.590 --> 00:00:50.950
and safety.

00:00:50.970 --> 00:00:56.670
So just by way of introduction, as Nick introduced me,

00:00:56.670 --> 00:00:58.080
I'm Julia.

00:00:58.090 --> 00:01:02.420
You also may know me as Scoyatolo, and

00:01:02.420 --> 00:01:07.700
I am not sure why that slide didn't advance.

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:11.700
There we go.

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:15.480
And I have been for the last two years running Skywatch

00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:16.140
Blue.

00:01:16.170 --> 00:01:18.320
Now, I'm going to preface this by saying that

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:20.990
this isn't exactly the talk that I set out to just

00:01:20.990 --> 00:01:24.670
, you know, share, you know, when I proposed

00:01:24.670 --> 00:01:25.770
this talk.

00:01:25.790 --> 00:01:28.740
After this weekend, you know, talking to folks, I

00:01:28.740 --> 00:01:31.730
've been constantly tweaking the presentation.

00:01:31.790 --> 00:01:34.130
And if I had time following Dr.

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:36.120
K, I probably would have made some changes because I learned

00:01:36.130 --> 00:01:40.100
some things during that talk that apply to some of the things

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:41.780
that I'm going to say.

00:01:41.790 --> 00:01:47.150
So, what are labels?

00:01:47.170 --> 00:01:51.390
Labels are metadata.

00:01:51.410 --> 00:01:59.950
And this is the sort of actual definition provided

00:01:59.950 --> 00:02:03.020
by the AT proto docs.

00:02:03.030 --> 00:02:07.000
And it's kind of, it's a long explanation.

00:02:07.030 --> 00:02:10.390
But the two things sort of to keep in mind about them

00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:14.010
is that they're a form of metadata about any account or

00:02:14.590 --> 00:02:16.640
content in the AT proto ecosystem.

00:02:16.650 --> 00:02:20.220
They sort of exist as freestanding objects.

00:02:20.230 --> 00:02:23.520
And they can be used for moderation purposes.

00:02:23.530 --> 00:02:26.160
But they can also be used for other purposes.

00:02:26.170 --> 00:02:29.300
And there's quite a few labelers out there that are

00:02:29.300 --> 00:02:31.580
sort of novelty or fun labelers.

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:33.720
All right.

00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:37.100
So I have an issue here where the slides don't exactly

00:02:37.250 --> 00:02:40.480
advance with sort of part that has the notes.

00:02:40.490 --> 00:02:44.170
So if it takes me a moment to move between slides,

00:02:44.170 --> 00:02:45.380
I apologize.

00:02:45.390 --> 00:02:48.780
So what is Skywatch?

00:02:48.790 --> 00:02:51.980
It is a general purpose labeling service.

00:02:51.990 --> 00:02:54.940
It's one of the largest, well, it might be

00:02:54.940 --> 00:02:58.590
one of the largest community labelers on BlueSky.

00:02:58.610 --> 00:03:01.500
There's no actual way to measure that other than by who

00:03:01.500 --> 00:03:05.220
has sort of clicked the heart button on the labeler.

00:03:05.230 --> 00:03:08.420
Which doesn't subscribe you to the labeler, by the

00:03:08.420 --> 00:03:08.940
way.

00:03:08.950 --> 00:03:11.480
It's possibly a cautionary tale.

00:03:11.510 --> 00:03:15.540
And it is definitely a personal project that got out of hand

00:03:15.570 --> 00:03:15.900
.

00:03:15.910 --> 00:03:21.770
Hence the picture of Fred Thompson in A Hunt for Red October

00:03:21.770 --> 00:03:25.140
where he's doing this business will get out of hand,

00:03:25.140 --> 00:03:26.540
it will get out of hand, and we'll be lucky

00:03:26.540 --> 00:03:28.720
to live through it.

00:03:28.730 --> 00:03:30.790
I would also like to note, and I will come back

00:03:30.790 --> 00:03:32.960
to this in a couple of slides, Skywatch is an

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:35.680
inherently political project.

00:03:35.690 --> 00:03:40.840
Not exactly in the way you think, but in the sense

00:03:40.880 --> 00:03:44.740
that all labelers are political.

00:03:44.750 --> 00:03:47.090
So what is Skywatch not?

00:03:47.230 --> 00:03:52.640
Well, Skywatch is not a community.

00:03:52.650 --> 00:04:01.230
And this is worth noting, it is a community service

00:04:01.230 --> 00:04:07.690
, but one of the sort of key things to remember about

00:04:07.690 --> 00:04:10.990
Skywatch is that it started with a few dozen users in

00:04:10.990 --> 00:04:11.600
mind.

00:04:11.610 --> 00:04:16.120
And it grew at a slow rate until November of 2024,

00:04:16.120 --> 00:04:21.060
paralleling sites growth, at which point it exploded by an

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:23.160
order of magnitude.

00:04:23.170 --> 00:04:26.430
I guess to that end, it's also hard to say

00:04:26.670 --> 00:04:29.710
that it serves a specific community.

00:04:29.730 --> 00:04:34.160
And one thing I haven't cracked is what to do about

00:04:34.210 --> 00:04:34.980
that.

00:04:35.010 --> 00:04:38.560
If you start with an original community of a few dozen,

00:04:38.570 --> 00:04:42.450
and now you are up at potentially 8,000 or more

00:04:42.450 --> 00:04:47.220
users who come from maybe backgrounds that you didn't originally plan

00:04:47.290 --> 00:04:51.400
for, it's hard to say how to serve them best

00:04:51.490 --> 00:04:51.870
.

00:04:51.910 --> 00:04:55.780
I also believe that Skywatch isn't a moderation service.

00:04:55.790 --> 00:04:58.280
We're not doing traditional trust and safety.

00:04:58.290 --> 00:05:01.790
We're also not -- we don't have takedown

00:05:01.850 --> 00:05:03.450
capabilities.

00:05:03.490 --> 00:05:05.620
Labelers are metadata.

00:05:05.630 --> 00:05:08.720
You can have block lists associated with certain labels, which we

00:05:08.720 --> 00:05:11.560
do, but block lists are soft moderation in the sense that

00:05:11.720 --> 00:05:14.440
they don't necessarily affect -- they don't affect taked

00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:14.900
owns.

00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:19.540
There was a recent paper actually published, which talked about the

00:05:19.590 --> 00:05:23.570
fact that they don't really break up the social graph either

00:05:23.570 --> 00:05:23.860
.

00:05:23.870 --> 00:05:26.470
And that's probably a good thing, even though the block

00:05:26.470 --> 00:05:29.840
on blue sky is understood to be a nuclear block.

00:05:29.850 --> 00:05:34.840
I will say that most labelers are not hard moderation.

00:05:34.850 --> 00:05:39.540
Some exceptions would be, you know, black sky, north

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:43.410
sky, and of course, blue sky moderation.

00:05:43.430 --> 00:05:50.540
So then -- by way of example, I just wanted to

00:05:50.580 --> 00:05:56.720
show some of the labels that we sort of append to content

00:05:56.720 --> 00:05:56.980
.

00:05:56.990 --> 00:06:00.540
I've broken them out by account versus post.

00:06:00.550 --> 00:06:03.240
And when I say that we're appending metadata, that

00:06:03.240 --> 00:06:04.980
's exactly what we're doing.

00:06:04.990 --> 00:06:07.790
We're analyzing the content in one way or another, some

00:06:07.800 --> 00:06:10.720
of it via automation, some of it via manual review,

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:14.420
and then we are applying a label based on the rules and

00:06:14.420 --> 00:06:20.600
the definitions of the label that we provide.

00:06:20.610 --> 00:06:23.950
So I do want to, before I go on further,

00:06:24.080 --> 00:06:29.630
go back to the notion that Skywatch is an inherently political

00:06:29.630 --> 00:06:30.160
project.

00:06:30.170 --> 00:06:33.630
And to do that, I want to talk a little bit

00:06:33.730 --> 00:06:35.920
about why I started it.

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:38.120
In 2018, I co-authored a paper with Kate

00:06:38.120 --> 00:06:41.470
Starbird and her team at the University of Washington that looked

00:06:41.470 --> 00:06:45.190
at the media ecosystem around the Syrian civil defense, also known

00:06:45.190 --> 00:06:49.390
as the White Helmets, in Syria during that country

00:06:49.390 --> 00:06:50.830
's civil war.

00:06:50.890 --> 00:06:52.760
And we started with Twitter.

00:06:52.770 --> 00:06:55.440
Some of her team went on to analyze other platforms.

00:06:55.450 --> 00:06:58.040
And what we found was that there was an active attempt to

00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:03.440
reshape the information space through content sharing and remixing across

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:07.490
multiple sites, domains, and political leanings to create the

00:07:07.490 --> 00:07:10.440
appearance of independent confirmation.

00:07:10.450 --> 00:07:12.720
The goal was to contest the civilian status of the White Hel

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:17.440
mets and legitimize their targeting under international law.

00:07:17.450 --> 00:07:21.220
Skywatch came about because Blue Sky offered a means to shape

00:07:21.220 --> 00:07:23.390
my personal information space.

00:07:23.450 --> 00:07:26.680
And the information space of anybody who chose to use the lab

00:07:26.740 --> 00:07:31.400
eler, which at the time was a small handful, well

00:07:31.400 --> 00:07:34.440
, a few dozen people.

00:07:34.450 --> 00:07:36.790
And I think it's important to remember that all labelers

00:07:36.830 --> 00:07:39.340
and content moderation do this to some extent.

00:07:39.350 --> 00:07:43.030
And whether the admins of it are conscious of it or

00:07:43.030 --> 00:07:46.010
not, we should be honest about that.

00:07:46.030 --> 00:07:48.330
And so I've always tried to be open about my motivations

00:07:48.330 --> 00:07:51.440
, which is that Skywatch is opinionated.

00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:54.030
It embodies a set of values and ideas about what users

00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:55.760
want to see on their timelines.

00:07:55.770 --> 00:07:58.070
And so this is what I mean when I say the project

00:07:58.140 --> 00:07:59.740
is inherently political.

00:07:59.770 --> 00:08:06.160
However, there are a couple other reasons why I started it

00:08:06.240 --> 00:08:06.720
.

00:08:06.730 --> 00:08:08.680
Jerry Nerd sniped me.

00:08:08.690 --> 00:08:13.120
So the first label was really the Blue Sky Elder label,

00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:19.720
which follows basically the criteria laid out here.

00:08:19.730 --> 00:08:24.230
And then next is, and content warning, but my partner

00:08:24.230 --> 00:08:27.480
who's in the room created this monstrosity,

00:08:27.490 --> 00:08:30.650
and it became part of early Blue Sky culture, which is

00:08:30.650 --> 00:08:32.710
why we have a Sensual ALF label.

00:08:32.730 --> 00:08:38.250
Yes, there are community standards, and I am trying to

00:08:38.250 --> 00:08:39.390
live up to them here.

00:08:39.410 --> 00:08:40.400
All right.

00:08:40.410 --> 00:08:43.820
So you want to start a label, a labeler,

00:08:43.970 --> 00:08:47.010
and a non-novelty labeler at that.

00:08:47.050 --> 00:08:53.650
I think the first thing I'll say is, don't

00:08:53.730 --> 00:08:54.280
.

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:57.400
If you do, you're probably someone who enjoys getting yelled

00:08:57.400 --> 00:08:57.720
at.

00:08:57.730 --> 00:09:00.600
You're now a mod, whether you like it or not

00:09:00.600 --> 00:09:05.640
, even though I said we're not a moderation service.

00:09:05.650 --> 00:09:09.280
Every label is going to be perceived as a personal attack.

00:09:09.290 --> 00:09:12.840
I mentioned you're getting yelled at.

00:09:12.850 --> 00:09:15.080
Which to be fair to users, we don't have,

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:17.460
if you're not hosting a PDS and having a lab

00:09:17.470 --> 00:09:19.910
eler associated with the PDS, you have no way to

00:09:19.910 --> 00:09:21.720
do the two-way communication.

00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:24.090
You can get appeals in, but you can't explain to

00:09:24.130 --> 00:09:27.240
people why they were labeled in a private manner.

00:09:27.250 --> 00:09:31.040
There's no way to send them an email, and that

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:33.730
's a shortfall of the tooling.

00:09:33.810 --> 00:09:38.440
Folks don't read the label definitions, except for the rules

00:09:38.440 --> 00:09:42.700
layers, and they're always going to be trying to sort

00:09:42.750 --> 00:09:47.300
of work you to get the rules, sort of either talk

00:09:47.380 --> 00:09:51.180
you into removing a label from them or to apply a label

00:09:51.180 --> 00:09:54.760
to someone else because they think it fits your definition.

00:09:54.770 --> 00:09:57.280
And I think a lot of folks, this is getting a

00:09:57.280 --> 00:09:59.950
little bit better, but I think a lot of folks don

00:09:59.950 --> 00:10:02.530
't understand what community labels are and can't necessarily tell the

00:10:02.530 --> 00:10:06.720
difference between you and blue sky.

00:10:06.770 --> 00:10:13.980
So, one thing you're going to have to learn is

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:19.420
that, I'm not sure, I'm sorry, your

00:10:19.420 --> 00:10:21.220
signals are noisy.

00:10:21.230 --> 00:10:28.620
And there we go.

00:10:28.630 --> 00:10:34.280
Many of your user-generated signals are noisy.

00:10:34.290 --> 00:10:36.850
You are, to a subset of users, going to be

00:10:36.850 --> 00:10:40.320
a gun and they are going to attempt to weaponize you

00:10:40.320 --> 00:10:40.820
.

00:10:40.830 --> 00:10:44.950
But, as I said before, lots of folks don't

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:49.590
necessarily read the labels and, as such, they're going

00:10:49.610 --> 00:10:53.420
to submit a lot of reports that have nothing to do with

00:10:53.420 --> 00:10:55.880
the things you label, per se.

00:10:55.890 --> 00:11:01.170
Case in point, we are constantly getting reports of things that

00:11:01.210 --> 00:11:02.980
people suspect are AI.

00:11:02.990 --> 00:11:06.620
Now, they are not necessarily misrepresenting what they

00:11:06.620 --> 00:11:07.100
are.

00:11:07.130 --> 00:11:12.040
I discovered this morning, people had started reporting Addy.

00:11:12.050 --> 00:11:15.220
It's just a fact of life.

00:11:15.230 --> 00:11:20.100
And user reports are noisy.

00:11:20.110 --> 00:11:22.910
Automation can fix some of this, but automation is also

00:11:22.920 --> 00:11:24.960
capable of making mistakes at scale.

00:11:24.970 --> 00:11:30.600
So there's always going to be risks inherent in either approach

00:11:30.600 --> 00:11:30.910
.

00:11:31.010 --> 00:11:36.040
Now in conversation with Luca and Juliette earlier this weekend,

00:11:36.040 --> 00:11:39.000
one thing that did come up is that there are ways to

00:11:39.380 --> 00:11:41.850
mitigate this through tweaks to the reporting workflow.

00:11:41.870 --> 00:11:43.510
So Brian, I'm sorry, you're probably going to

00:11:43.510 --> 00:11:47.830
get some GitHub issues from either me or Luca, requesting changes

00:11:47.920 --> 00:11:49.980
when you all have the time.

00:11:49.990 --> 00:11:56.820
And this is difficult if you don't control the reporting workflow

00:11:56.820 --> 00:11:57.260
.

00:11:57.270 --> 00:12:02.020
Scale is very hard.

00:12:02.030 --> 00:12:04.800
And if we go back to the fact that, yeah,

00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:08.350
I know, I went fully insane and I think the website

00:12:08.350 --> 00:12:11.940
probably, you know, was going through some things.

00:12:11.970 --> 00:12:15.610
Although interestingly, well, I'll get to it in a

00:12:15.610 --> 00:12:19.650
minute, but remember, so growth can be a bit of

00:12:19.650 --> 00:12:22.700
a curse, especially with a general purpose labeler.

00:12:22.710 --> 00:12:26.300
You know, one of the things that makes this difficult is

00:12:26.300 --> 00:12:29.820
not having a specific community that you serve makes it a little

00:12:29.820 --> 00:12:32.260
bit harder to find and onboard volunteers.

00:12:32.270 --> 00:12:37.880
So it's something to keep in mind.

00:12:37.890 --> 00:12:40.400
So we had an eternal November that, well, not,

00:12:40.400 --> 00:12:41.280
not eternal.

00:12:41.290 --> 00:12:43.880
It lasted about five months.

00:12:43.910 --> 00:12:47.560
We were getting, so November was 70,000 reports,

00:12:47.560 --> 00:12:49.190
November 2024.

00:12:49.230 --> 00:12:53.000
And interestingly, I was talking to Brian and this was actually

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.830
different for them because, because we don't deal with things

00:12:55.830 --> 00:12:56.760
like sexual content.

00:12:56.770 --> 00:12:59.110
We didn't have to deal with the flood of reports that

00:12:59.190 --> 00:13:02.710
came in when video was rolled out.

00:13:02.790 --> 00:13:05.800
So it's essentially unique to each labeler and kind of

00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:11.240
what your labels are and what people perceive that you are covering

00:13:11.310 --> 00:13:11.660
.

00:13:11.670 --> 00:13:15.200
Reports began climbing, you know, right after election week or

00:13:15.230 --> 00:13:16.160
election day.

00:13:16.170 --> 00:13:19.660
They peaked in November 20th or so.

00:13:19.670 --> 00:13:24.590
And then there was a steady decline over the next four to

00:13:24.590 --> 00:13:26.040
five months.

00:13:26.070 --> 00:13:29.160
One thing I think that helped was that Blue Sky made some

00:13:29.250 --> 00:13:33.100
changes to the reporting workflow so that you could no longer sort

00:13:33.100 --> 00:13:37.280
of shotgun report content to every single labeler you subscribe to

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:37.880
.

00:13:37.890 --> 00:13:41.240
It forced you to be a little bit more nuanced.

00:13:41.250 --> 00:13:46.060
And we've now settled out at a baseline of between three

00:13:46.060 --> 00:13:49.520
to 7,000 reports a month.

00:13:49.530 --> 00:13:50.860
It varies.

00:13:50.870 --> 00:13:54.120
And I suspect that as we get closer to midterms

00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:58.910
, we'll probably see a spike there as well as people

00:13:59.160 --> 00:14:07.430
start reporting certain content to Skywatch

00:14:07.430 --> 00:14:08.100
.

00:14:08.170 --> 00:14:12.720
So the other thing to keep in mind is that you're

00:14:12.720 --> 00:14:16.380
going to create new affordances.

00:14:16.390 --> 00:14:18.730
And some of them are going to suck.

00:14:18.850 --> 00:14:21.190
And you should undo your mistake.

00:14:21.330 --> 00:14:24.160
So this is actually not a screenshot of Skywatch.

00:14:24.170 --> 00:14:26.510
This labeler would put a badge on your account if you

00:14:26.590 --> 00:14:30.330
followed one of these individuals with the theory of change being that

00:14:30.390 --> 00:14:33.300
by making this legible, which is what labels do,

00:14:33.300 --> 00:14:38.040
they make certain things and behaviors legible.

00:14:38.070 --> 00:14:41.490
It would cause users to shun certain accounts and some social

00:14:41.600 --> 00:14:44.340
pressure for folks to unfollow those people.

00:14:44.350 --> 00:14:48.780
Unfortunately, it facilitated abuse, which is why it no

00:14:48.830 --> 00:14:50.260
longer exists.

00:14:50.270 --> 00:14:52.340
So you're going to make mistakes.

00:14:52.350 --> 00:14:54.320
Some of them are going to be innocuous.

00:14:54.410 --> 00:14:57.340
Slurs, for example, are hard to do, to

00:14:57.340 --> 00:14:59.730
sort of automatically flag.

00:14:59.750 --> 00:15:04.040
You'll decide one day that you want to label an unfortunately

00:15:04.040 --> 00:15:07.030
far too common English language slur, ableist slur

00:15:07.030 --> 00:15:08.860
, go to bed and you're going to wake up with

00:15:08.860 --> 00:15:12.580
the francophone world mad at you because you forgot that it

00:15:12.580 --> 00:15:15.610
's a benign vocabulary word in French.

00:15:15.630 --> 00:15:19.960
And so you need to approach these things with some nuance and

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:23.400
fortunately we have the tooling to do.

00:15:23.410 --> 00:15:25.920
So, though imperfect as it is, we do have the

00:15:25.920 --> 00:15:35.300
tooling to determine what language a given post is in.

00:15:35.310 --> 00:15:40.370
So you're going to want to label behavior and facts,

00:15:40.450 --> 00:15:42.140
not identity.

00:15:42.150 --> 00:15:45.030
And you're going to want to do it consistently with your

00:15:45.030 --> 00:15:46.260
label definitions.

00:15:46.330 --> 00:15:49.070
I think it should go without saying, but don't li

00:15:49.070 --> 00:15:49.980
bel people.

00:15:49.990 --> 00:15:51.960
Document your claims.

00:15:51.990 --> 00:15:53.880
Be ethical.

00:15:53.890 --> 00:15:58.930
You probably want to check your renter's or homeowner

00:15:58.930 --> 00:16:03.130
's insurance to make sure that, if you're not a

00:16:03.130 --> 00:16:06.270
business this is, to make sure that you have just a

00:16:06.270 --> 00:16:10.400
sort of universal umbrella coverage in case somebody decides to hit you

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:11.660
with a slap lawsuit.

00:16:11.670 --> 00:16:15.540
You are generally covered, at least from the conversations I've

00:16:15.540 --> 00:16:21.630
had with lawyers, you are generally covered under section 230,

00:16:21.630 --> 00:16:23.670
if -- Or not.

00:16:23.690 --> 00:16:24.680
Or not.

00:16:24.690 --> 00:16:26.580
Don't build up to it.

00:16:26.590 --> 00:16:27.580
Yes.

00:16:27.590 --> 00:16:28.580
Yes.

00:16:28.590 --> 00:16:30.920
Thank Ron Wyden for fighting a good fight.

00:16:30.930 --> 00:16:35.800
But, you know, your mileage may vary by jurisdiction,

00:16:35.800 --> 00:16:39.660
of course, and, you know, there's absolutely no

00:16:39.660 --> 00:16:43.820
certainty, you know, in a climate where speech is generally

00:16:43.820 --> 00:16:45.450
highly politicized.

00:16:45.510 --> 00:16:49.780
But, labelers can be fun, and I, you

00:16:49.780 --> 00:16:55.700
know, don't want to just talk about the negative parts

00:16:55.730 --> 00:16:56.720
of it.

00:16:56.730 --> 00:17:01.640
And so, there are affordances of labelers, and

00:17:01.640 --> 00:17:05.680
this is not really in Skywatch's remit, but

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:09.500
I was testing whether or not I could use Osprey

00:17:09.500 --> 00:17:14.360
's database to figure out who was the top Taylor Swift listener

00:17:14.360 --> 00:17:18.450
that day using, you know, using the Clickhouse database

00:17:18.540 --> 00:17:20.610
, and using teal.

00:17:20.610 --> 00:17:22.720
fm's lexicon.

00:17:22.730 --> 00:17:23.720
And I could.

00:17:23.730 --> 00:17:25.700
And it was pretty simple.

00:17:25.730 --> 00:17:28.620
And, you know, it's kind of funny, because

00:17:28.620 --> 00:17:33.120
then you can kind of go from there and independently invent something

00:17:33.120 --> 00:17:36.060
very similar to Addy, where you take the posts of

00:17:36.090 --> 00:17:37.350
the top teal.

00:17:37.370 --> 00:17:40.990
fm listeners of Taylor Swift tracks, and you just find

00:17:40.990 --> 00:17:43.690
some of their posts, and now you have a feed that

00:17:43.710 --> 00:17:44.940
you could potentially create.

00:17:44.950 --> 00:17:47.150
Again, not really within the scope of what we do,

00:17:47.150 --> 00:17:50.750
but I do want to sort of point out that that label

00:17:50.760 --> 00:17:53.950
ers can be fun.

00:17:53.970 --> 00:17:57.520
So looking a bit to the future, I want to talk

00:17:57.530 --> 00:18:02.460
a bit about some of the tools available to make this a

00:18:02.460 --> 00:18:05.320
little bit easier.

00:18:05.330 --> 00:18:08.560
So if you follow me on Blue Sky, you've probably

00:18:08.800 --> 00:18:10.800
seen a graph similar to this.

00:18:10.810 --> 00:18:13.580
This is a graph of the sort of the Gaza Spam

00:18:13.580 --> 00:18:17.640
accounts that have cropped up in the last two weeks.

00:18:17.650 --> 00:18:23.160
The accounts where they are recycling the same set of usern

00:18:23.160 --> 00:18:27.600
ames or the same set of profiles, and doing things like

00:18:27.600 --> 00:18:30.580
reposting people so it just shows up in their mentions

00:18:30.590 --> 00:18:30.840
.

00:18:30.890 --> 00:18:34.750
It is generally a good indicator of inauthentic behavior

00:18:34.750 --> 00:18:38.640
, and we're labeling it as inauthenticity.

00:18:38.650 --> 00:18:43.810
And I know that this specific case is controversial, but this

00:18:43.840 --> 00:18:46.180
is more by way of example.

00:18:46.270 --> 00:18:48.190
To do this, I would never have been able to do

00:18:48.190 --> 00:18:51.600
this or detect this at scale, just using ozone and manually

00:18:51.720 --> 00:18:53.190
labeling things.

00:18:53.210 --> 00:19:01.660
So we can make it suck less by using better tools.

00:19:01.670 --> 00:19:06.460
So our automod started as a bash script, this was

00:19:06.460 --> 00:19:08.150
two years ago.

00:19:08.210 --> 00:19:11.750
That lasted about a year, I rewrote it in

00:19:11.770 --> 00:19:15.160
TypeScript, and now we use Osprey.

00:19:15.170 --> 00:19:17.500
And it's great.

00:19:17.710 --> 00:19:21.810
We also use, it's Osprey plus ozone.

00:19:21.830 --> 00:19:26.230
And then I use Claude and a stack of skills and

00:19:26.230 --> 00:19:30.940
tools to help me rapidly query the database.

00:19:30.950 --> 00:19:33.290
So Claude is not making, now you see here Cla

00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:36.910
ude has opinions, but Claude is not making judgments or

00:19:36.910 --> 00:19:38.760
content moderation decisions.

00:19:38.850 --> 00:19:43.770
I've actually experimented in the past with trying to use

00:19:43.770 --> 00:19:47.550
LLMs to assess individual pieces of content, and there

00:19:47.550 --> 00:19:49.840
's just not enough information there, at least for the tools

00:19:49.840 --> 00:19:51.140
I was using.

00:19:51.150 --> 00:19:54.190
Now, there are probably more sophisticated tools, there's fine

00:19:54.190 --> 00:19:58.400
tuning you can probably do to get your accuracy up.

00:19:58.470 --> 00:20:01.910
But for the most part, what I find it extremely useful

00:20:02.030 --> 00:20:04.860
for is going out, querying Ozone, querying

00:20:04.930 --> 00:20:08.200
the ClickHouse database to put together reports that I can

00:20:08.400 --> 00:20:12.070
then dive deeper into to see is this really a signal or

00:20:12.070 --> 00:20:15.450
is this just something spurious?

00:20:15.510 --> 00:20:18.210
And in this case, I have, to illustrate it,

00:20:18.210 --> 00:20:22.170
you know, there's basically a small network of accounts via

00:20:22.170 --> 00:20:25.280
, you know, coming via Bridgifed that are

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:29.420
sort of reposting what you would consider, you know

00:20:29.420 --> 00:20:34.530
, Russian military telegram copy pasta and sort of other,

00:20:34.530 --> 00:20:40.870
you can call it propaganda, other content aimed at various different

00:20:40.880 --> 00:20:42.320
language groups.

00:20:42.330 --> 00:20:47.020
It's a relatively small number, but it's there.

00:20:47.030 --> 00:20:50.720
And, you know, if you have these tools, it

00:20:50.720 --> 00:20:53.280
's relatively easy to find.

00:20:53.290 --> 00:20:55.870
You know, and to that end, I've been building

00:20:55.890 --> 00:20:58.920
some of those tools such as sidecar services to do,

00:20:58.920 --> 00:21:01.360
you know, Poisson analysis on PDS sign ups,

00:21:01.360 --> 00:21:04.820
you know, looking at URL over dispersion, doing some

00:21:04.820 --> 00:21:10.430
lighting clustering and account entropy calculations to help detect that activity

00:21:10.430 --> 00:21:10.610
.

00:21:10.650 --> 00:21:12.620
I'll say that those are noisy signals.

00:21:12.650 --> 00:21:14.980
So, by themselves, they shouldn't be sort of relied

00:21:14.980 --> 00:21:15.480
upon.

00:21:15.490 --> 00:21:18.400
So, human review is still important and correlation is still important

00:21:18.400 --> 00:21:20.550
between sources, between signals.

00:21:20.650 --> 00:21:23.680
And I just want to end on the note that automation is

00:21:23.680 --> 00:21:28.600
not perfect, it can make mistakes, but it's a

00:21:28.600 --> 00:21:31.950
lot easier than trying to find these things just using regular expressions

00:21:31.950 --> 00:21:35.180
or just using, you know, searches on Blue Sky.

00:21:35.190 --> 00:21:40.750
And since our users subscribe for, especially for some of the

00:21:40.750 --> 00:21:44.330
sort of, you know, authenticity labels, it's important

00:21:44.330 --> 00:21:47.120
for us to kind of proactively search for these things.

00:21:47.130 --> 00:21:53.730
So, what is the future of unintegrated labelers

00:21:53.810 --> 00:21:54.340
?

00:21:54.350 --> 00:21:56.930
And by unintegrated labelers, I mean what Sky

00:21:56.930 --> 00:21:57.660
watch is.

00:21:57.670 --> 00:22:02.920
We are not affiliated with a set of PDSs or

00:22:02.920 --> 00:22:05.540
an app view in the way that Blue Sky is or that

00:22:05.540 --> 00:22:08.970
Black Sky is.

00:22:08.990 --> 00:22:13.350
Now, my theory is that, because the atmosphere is growing

00:22:13.350 --> 00:22:16.440
, that not every application or PDS admin or relay owner

00:22:16.440 --> 00:22:18.180
is going to want to set up their own full-st

00:22:18.180 --> 00:22:19.440
ack moderation service.

00:22:19.450 --> 00:22:25.140
They are going to need trusted signals to action content and accounts

00:22:25.140 --> 00:22:26.050
on their network.

00:22:26.070 --> 00:22:31.320
A great example, excuse me, is PDS admins

00:22:31.370 --> 00:22:31.380
.

00:22:31.390 --> 00:22:33.730
And I want to give a shout-out to Bailey for

00:22:33.810 --> 00:22:35.500
building Label Watcher.

00:22:35.530 --> 00:22:41.260
If you haven't talked to Bailey about it, this is

00:22:41.260 --> 00:22:45.960
a tool for a PDS admin or any other piece of

00:22:45.960 --> 00:22:50.490
infrastructure to watch the firehose coming off of a set

00:22:50.490 --> 00:22:51.340
of labelers.

00:22:51.350 --> 00:22:54.720
And then it can either email you to tell you when a

00:22:54.910 --> 00:22:59.570
label of interest is detected being admitted against an account on your

00:22:59.570 --> 00:23:03.820
PDS or it can automate the takedown.

00:23:03.830 --> 00:23:06.750
And the nice thing about that, it is up to you

00:23:06.750 --> 00:23:10.190
as the admin to make a decision whether you trust the lab

00:23:10.220 --> 00:23:12.500
eler enough to actually do the takedown.

00:23:12.530 --> 00:23:17.540
And so as a result, we have this new group that

00:23:17.540 --> 00:23:24.040
previously wasn't considered a user that is now a user.

00:23:24.050 --> 00:23:27.940
And so Skywatch is one of the signals for catching spam

00:23:27.940 --> 00:23:31.910
accounts created on self-hosted social and PMX social

00:23:31.910 --> 00:23:32.280
.

00:23:32.290 --> 00:23:35.540
So thank you, Bailey, for building this and also for

00:23:35.810 --> 00:23:37.720
placing your trust in Skywatch.

00:23:37.730 --> 00:23:46.370
I think we nerd sniped ourselves with that one

00:23:46.380 --> 00:23:47.140
.

00:23:47.150 --> 00:23:53.190
So now I do just want to talk about this a little

00:23:53.210 --> 00:23:57.690
bit because the previous slide we talked a little bit about how

00:23:57.750 --> 00:24:01.620
Skywatch can be used by PDS admins.

00:24:01.630 --> 00:24:05.750
And I want to note that labelers are an informal governance

00:24:05.800 --> 00:24:07.670
institution in a sense.

00:24:07.730 --> 00:24:10.070
In a commons that, you know, as it grows

00:24:10.140 --> 00:24:13.650
, it's going to lack formal governance over the whole comm

00:24:13.650 --> 00:24:14.210
ons.

00:24:14.230 --> 00:24:17.020
Blue sky is going to take responsibility for certain parts of it

00:24:17.020 --> 00:24:17.260
.

00:24:17.270 --> 00:24:19.900
Other parts of it, other folks will.

00:24:19.910 --> 00:24:22.250
And other parts of it may be somewhat ungoverned.

00:24:22.370 --> 00:24:26.260
We should remember that labelers are embodying sort of a

00:24:26.260 --> 00:24:28.540
form of power and authority.

00:24:28.550 --> 00:24:30.740
They're agents which act on the network.

00:24:30.750 --> 00:24:34.620
And we should also note that some of these tools are incredibly

00:24:34.620 --> 00:24:37.230
powerful surveillance mechanisms.

00:24:37.250 --> 00:24:39.920
And so they need to be used ethically.

00:24:39.930 --> 00:24:41.600
We need moderation.

00:24:41.610 --> 00:24:43.780
But that, by its nature, is surveillance.

00:24:43.790 --> 00:24:46.580
And so seeing like a moderator means trying to take behavior and

00:24:46.580 --> 00:24:48.880
activity and making it legible.

00:24:48.890 --> 00:24:51.580
And that creates the temptation to fence in the commons,

00:24:51.580 --> 00:24:55.220
categorize people in behavior in a binary fashion, and then

00:24:55.220 --> 00:24:57.760
tightly define what's right and wrong, as Dr.

00:24:57.760 --> 00:25:00.440
K sort of had alluded to.

00:25:00.450 --> 00:25:06.230
Or, sorry, no, that was a previous session in

00:25:06.230 --> 00:25:08.440
here that was Dr.

00:25:08.630 --> 00:25:10.360
Blackwell.

00:25:10.370 --> 00:25:12.570
We don't want to fence in the commons entirely.

00:25:12.590 --> 00:25:15.700
We want to be able to sort of set norms and set

00:25:15.700 --> 00:25:19.480
the rules to govern the parts of the commons that we

00:25:19.480 --> 00:25:24.590
care about that are within our jurisdiction without trying to restrict how

00:25:24.590 --> 00:25:26.660
everyone else can act.

00:25:26.670 --> 00:25:32.440
All right, I am very close to wrapping up then,

00:25:32.440 --> 00:25:34.380
so thank you.

00:25:34.390 --> 00:25:38.020
I do want to talk about the elephant in the dark forest

00:25:38.020 --> 00:25:41.050
, because I'm an independent labeler.

00:25:41.070 --> 00:25:44.860
If you've not read or watched the three-body problem

00:25:44.860 --> 00:25:48.970
, the dark forest metaphor is the idea that all advanced gal

00:25:49.300 --> 00:25:52.340
actic civilizations are locked in a bit of real-life game

00:25:52.370 --> 00:25:57.820
theory, which the annihilation of any other civilization that they

00:25:57.820 --> 00:26:01.060
encounter is the only correct move.

00:26:01.070 --> 00:26:03.400
And this is kind of a tortured metaphor, because I was

00:26:03.420 --> 00:26:06.440
going for the elephant in the room plus the dark forest,

00:26:06.690 --> 00:26:10.740
and I don't necessarily want to cast dispersions on elephants

00:26:10.740 --> 00:26:11.080
.

00:26:11.090 --> 00:26:12.700
But I think we do need to talk a little bit about

00:26:12.700 --> 00:26:13.060
Aegis.

00:26:13.130 --> 00:26:14.980
If you don't know what Aegis was, it was

00:26:14.980 --> 00:26:17.160
one of the first independent labelers.

00:26:17.190 --> 00:26:19.530
The operator ended up using it for harassment, and I think

00:26:19.620 --> 00:26:22.390
it soured Blue Sky, both the community and the company

00:26:22.390 --> 00:26:26.140
, on the community labeler experiment for a while.

00:26:26.150 --> 00:26:28.770
And I want to remind people that I, as an individual

00:26:28.810 --> 00:26:32.980
, sometimes with help, sometimes with not, am running something

00:26:32.980 --> 00:26:37.240
that has the capability of being a surveillance platform.

00:26:37.250 --> 00:26:40.310
Labelers collapse context, and at scale, they could

00:26:40.730 --> 00:26:42.640
potentially break the social graph.

00:26:42.650 --> 00:26:48.290
And I think it's great that people put their trust in

00:26:48.290 --> 00:26:49.010
me.

00:26:49.030 --> 00:26:52.120
But by the same token, you shouldn't have to.

00:26:52.130 --> 00:26:55.440
You shouldn't have to trust that Fane will take away

00:26:55.600 --> 00:26:57.740
the keys if I suddenly go rogue.

00:26:57.750 --> 00:27:01.850
And you know, it's a bad model.

00:27:01.910 --> 00:27:04.580
In a previous life, I worked on issues of data ethics

00:27:04.580 --> 00:27:08.900
and privacy, and the harms technology can cause inhumanitarian

00:27:08.900 --> 00:27:10.020
response.

00:27:10.030 --> 00:27:13.210
Jay, quoting Melvin Kranzberg yesterday, I think

00:27:13.210 --> 00:27:14.360
was important.

00:27:14.370 --> 00:27:16.600
These tools are what we make of them.

00:27:16.650 --> 00:27:19.650
But we can't assume we're the only actors using them

00:27:19.650 --> 00:27:19.900
.

00:27:19.910 --> 00:27:26.820
And the assumption that we are acting in an ethical and just

00:27:26.820 --> 00:27:29.520
way, I want to think that I am.

00:27:29.530 --> 00:27:31.240
I want other people to think that I am.

00:27:31.250 --> 00:27:33.220
But I don't want you to have to rely on just

00:27:33.300 --> 00:27:33.740
that.

00:27:33.750 --> 00:27:37.650
And I think that we probably have to have some conversations as

00:27:37.650 --> 00:27:43.560
a sort of a community about how we govern the commons

00:27:43.560 --> 00:27:46.600
and how we govern labelers.

00:27:46.610 --> 00:27:52.810
So I would like to encourage people to come to the discourse

00:27:52.810 --> 00:27:58.680
and start discussions there and move us towards a composable moderation

00:27:58.690 --> 00:28:01.950
working group so we can set some standards and have some of

00:28:01.950 --> 00:28:02.900
these discussions.

00:28:02.910 --> 00:28:11.220
And I just want to wrap up with this quote from Lawrence

00:28:11.220 --> 00:28:17.480
, "An open protocol that does not answer the governance question

00:28:17.480 --> 00:28:19.860
will still receive an answer, yet it will be written by

00:28:19.890 --> 00:28:25.400
whichever actors make themselves indispensable first." And then I do want

00:28:25.400 --> 00:28:27.590
to finish on the note that I do think labelers are

00:28:27.590 --> 00:28:28.360
important.

00:28:28.370 --> 00:28:30.520
I think that they're incredibly useful.

00:28:30.530 --> 00:28:33.730
I think we have the opportunity to shape the spaces that we

00:28:33.730 --> 00:28:37.280
are sort of inhabiting for good.

00:28:37.290 --> 00:28:40.570
And so even though this talk has had pessimistic notes,

00:28:40.570 --> 00:28:42.910
I want to end on the note that you should check out

00:28:42.910 --> 00:28:43.500
some of these labelers.

00:28:43.510 --> 00:28:46.190
Skywatch is there, of course, but Lylabs

00:28:46.190 --> 00:28:49.040
, SteshLab, and Black Sky are also labelers

00:28:49.040 --> 00:28:49.760
that I use.

00:28:49.770 --> 00:28:53.870
I find valuable, and I hope you do too.

00:28:53.950 --> 00:28:56.020
And I think we are probably just at time, so I

00:28:56.020 --> 00:28:57.300
don't want to run over.

00:28:57.310 --> 00:28:58.650
But if there are any questions, I'm happy to hang

00:28:58.650 --> 00:28:59.800
out for a little bit and answer them.

00:29:01.420 --> 00:29:04.640
Thank you.
